------------------------------------------------Question 1 (5 points)--------------------------------------------------
A block cipher with an 8-bit block size is very easy to break with a known-plaintext attack, assuming each block is
just encrypted independently with the same key. Describe how you would do so.

Hint: There's a version of a very similar challenge in many newspapers every day called cryptograms.
Here's an example Links to an external site..

ANSWER------------------
The fact that this would be a 'known plaintext' attack implies that you already know the ciphertext - plaintext pairings,
and the nature of the cipher itself means that these pairings will stay the same even as more plaintext is decrypted.
So to break this cipher, you'd log the pairings you know and keep parsing through newly output ciphertext to determine
the rest of the pairings (there can only be 256 possible values, so it wouldn't take especially long to decipher).

Once you've logged all plaintext-ciphertext pairings, you'll be able to encode all past and future messages.

-----------------------------------------------Question 2 (10 points)-------------------------------------------------
Assume you're sending a long message using a block cipher (like AES) with the following scheme: split the message into
block-sized chunks, then encrypt each with the same key. Basically, Alice sends Bob AES(m1, k), AES(m2, k), AES(m3, k),
etc.

Part A (3 points)------------------
Even if they can't decrypt blocks, what information can an eavesdropper discern from this scheme? Hint: Imagine that
Alice is sending a table of data where each cell is exactly one block of data.

ANSWER------------------
They would be able to detect repeating patterns which, over time, can start to be interpreted as language/plaintext.

Part B (4 points)------------------
Things are actually even worse! A malicious attacker can actually CHANGE the message that Bob receives from Alice
(slightly). How? This is particularly bad if the attacker knows the structure of the data being sent (like in part A).

ANSWER------------------
Technically they could be employing a man-in-the-middle attack to actively change the text being transmitted, but under
the assumption that they still don't understand it - and only understand the patterns, as mentioned in part A - it's
more likely that any changes they make would be related to bit-flipping. For this type of attack specifically, they
wouldn't necessarily need to understand the exact text itself to alter it, which would then alter the plaintext when
it's decrypted later on.

Part C (3 points)------------------
How could you modify the scheme to mitigate/prevent these types of attack?

ANSWER------------------
Besides changing the type of cipher entirely, your other best bet would be to use an encryption schemes like the
Galois/Counter or ChaCha, which combine your original cipher with a MAC. This means that your message is changed by
a bad actor, it'll cause an authentication check to fail, and will outright discard the compromised message.